references: Within our new dataset, we use SlamToolbox [30] with LiDAR data to generate a ground truth trajectory. The comparison of radar with LiDAR trajectories is commonly applied in absence of more accurate ground truth measures, see, e.g., [9]. However, it should be noted that the state of the art in radar SLAM approaches the accuracy of LiDAR SLAM [6]. We perform ten runs for each scenario and in each parameter configuration. This accounts for slight variations in the performance measures due to the multi-threaded implementation. The indoor environment is tested with the indoor and mixed configuration, and the outdoor environment with the outdoor and mixed configuration. Using the indoor configuration on the outdoor environment and vice versa proofed to be infeasible (compare Section IV-B). In addition, we evaluate the specialized configurations without loop closure to demonstrate the improved performance enabled by the loop closure module. Table I lists ATE and RPE measures of the tests using the LiDAR trajectory as ground truth.

references: To assess the real-time capability, we evaluate the average duration spent by the most important subsystems (Table II). We measure the graph optimization each time new loop closure constraints are added to the graph. No robust measure for the standard deviation can be given in the outdoor sequence, as only two loop closures are detected in the trajectory. The pre-processing and motion estimation steps are performed synchronous. Therefore, the time spent on a complete cycle of RaNDT SLAM is significantly smaller than the sensor’s measurement cycle of 200200200 ms. This allows the online usage for autonomous operation and is promising for future radar sensors with higher scanning rate. The increased processing times in the indoor application are caused by the finer resolution of the NDT map. This leads to NDTs with more components, which makes the optimization more time consuming. Moreover, we observe that the indoor scenario takes approximately twice as long. This is because more distributions are generated, which makes the optimization harder. Note, that the cycle times are parameter-dependent and need to be considered as a trade-off between computational times, resolution and expected noise ratio.

references: To underline the applicability of RaNDT SLAM in different environments and with different sensor models, we test RaNDT SLAM on the Oxford dataset [27], using the provided GT obtained via visual odometry, visual loop closures, and GPS constraints. This allows us to compare our results with state-of-the-art radar SLAM and radar odometry approaches, partially introduced in Section II. Table III depicts the KITTI odometry errors and the ATEs. As the ATE largely favors algorithms using loop closure, we present only full SLAM systems and omit results obtained with radar odometry. The ATE achieved with RaNDT SLAM scores second-best just behind TBV SLAM [6]. In addition, the translation drift is able to keep up with other radar SLAM and radar odometry methods. Notably, we perform better than the other NDT-based methods regarding the translational drift [4, 38]. The rotational drift, however, is less competitive. We attribute this to the missing motion compensation in our framework, as motion distortion compromises the measurements especially during turns of the vehicle. We conclude, that RaNDT SLAM generalizes well to different domains and sensor types, although being designed for smaller-scale and indoor environments. We expect the performance to increase further if techniques tailored for autonomous driving datasets such as motion compensation [32] or origin shifting in descriptor generation [13] are implemented.
